In the treatment of Russian authors one will often (or maybe not so often) come across the word ''kalembur''. It means pun - and especially [[Nikolai Gogol]] is known for his extensive use of kalemburs in his texts. In 1919 the russian [[formalist]] Boris Ejchenbaum wrote a anticle about Gogol's short story "The Overcoat" in which he treats Gogols estensive use of kalemburs in his text. The article has become a classic in the [[literary formalism]].

See also: [[Russian formalism]].

